                </svg>
                Back to Main Page
            </button>
            <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-center text-slate-800 mb-8">Pharmacology</h1>
            <p class="text-lg text-center text-slate-600 max-w-3xl mx-auto mb-12">
                Welcome to the Pharmacology module. Here you'll explore the study of drugs, their actions, and their effects on living organisms.
            </p>
            
            <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-xl shadow-lg max-w-4xl mx-auto">
                <!-- Overview Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Introduction to Pharmacology</h3>
                    <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row items-center space-y-4 md:space-y-0 md:space-x-8">
                        <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 flex-1">
                            Pharmacology is the branch of medicine and biology concerned with the study of drug action, where a drug can be broadly defined as any artificial, natural, or endogenous substance which exerts a biochemical or physiological effect on the cell, tissue, organ, or organism.
                        </p>
                        <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/400x300/cbe5fa/0ea5e9?text=Drug+Molecule" alt="Diagram of a drug molecule" class="rounded-xl shadow-md">
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Pharmacodynamics Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Pharmacodynamics: What the drug does to the body</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 mb-4">
                        This involves the study of the biochemical, cellular, and physiological effects of drugs and their mechanism of action.
                    </p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                        <li><strong>Receptors:</strong> Most drugs work by binding to specific receptor molecules on or within a cell.</li>
                        <li><strong>Agonist:</strong> A drug that binds to a receptor and activates it to produce a biological response.</li>
                        <li><strong>Antagonist:</strong> A drug that binds to a receptor but does not activate it, thereby blocking an agonist's action.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <!-- Pharmacokinetics Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Pharmacokinetics: What the body does to the drug</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 mb-4">
                        This is the study of how the body absorbs, distributes, metabolizes, and excretes a drug. This is often summarized by the acronym **ADME**.
                    </p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                        <li><strong>Absorption:</strong> The movement of a drug from its site of administration into the bloodstream.</li>
                        <li><strong>Distribution:</strong> The transport of the drug by the bloodstream to its target tissues and organs.</li>
                        <li><strong>Metabolism:</strong> The process by which the body chemically alters the drug, primarily in the liver.</li>
                        <li><strong>Excretion:</strong> The elimination of the drug from the body, typically by the kidneys.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <!-- Clinical Applications Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Clinical Applications</h3>
                    <div class="bg-sky-50 p-6 rounded-lg shadow-inner">
                        <p class="text-lg text-slate-700">
                            Understanding pharmacology is crucial for prescribing drugs, determining correct dosages, and predicting potential side effects or drug interactions. It is the foundation of rational drug therapy in all fields of medicine.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>


    <!-- Skeletal System Page Content - Initially Hidden -->
    <div id="skeletal-system-page-content" class="page-content hidden py-16 md:py-24">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <button id="back-to-anatomy" class="flex items-center mb-8 text-sky-600 font-semibold hover:text-sky-800 transition-colors">
                <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-5 w-5 mr-2" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor">
                    <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M10 19l-7-7m0 0l7-7m-7 7h18" />
                </svg>
                Back to Anatomy
            </button>
            <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-center text-slate-800 mb-8">The Skeletal System</h1>
            <div class="bg-white p-8 rounded-xl shadow-lg max-w-4xl mx-auto">
                <!-- Overview Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Skeletal System Overview</h3>
                    <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row items-center space-y-4 md:space-y-0 md:space-x-8">
                        <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 flex-1">
                            The skeletal system is the structural framework of the human body. It is made up of bones, cartilage, ligaments, and joints, all working together to provide shape, support, protection, and movement. The average adult human skeleton consists of 206 bones, while infants are born with around 270 bones, some of which fuse as they grow.
                        </p>
                        <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/400x500/cbe5fa/0ea5e9?text=Human+Skeleton" alt="Diagram of the Human Skeleton" class="rounded-xl shadow-md">
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Major Functions Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Major Functions of the Skeletal System</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                        <li><strong>Support:</strong> Provides the rigid framework that supports the body and maintains its shape.</li>
                        <li><strong>Movement:</strong> Bones act as levers, while muscles attached to them via tendons allow motion.</li>
                        <li><strong>Protection:</strong> Vital organs are shielded by bones (e.g., skull protects the brain, rib cage protects heart and lungs).</li>
                        <li><strong>Mineral Storage:</strong> Bones store essential minerals, especially calcium and phosphorus, which can be released into the bloodstream as needed.</li>
                        <li><strong>Blood Cell Production (Hematopoiesis):</strong> The red bone marrow inside certain bones produces red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.</li>
                        <li><strong>Energy Storage:</strong> Yellow bone marrow stores fat, which serves as an energy reserve.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <!-- Divisions Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Divisions of the Skeleton</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 mb-4">
                        The human skeleton is divided into two main parts:
                    </p>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                        <div class="bg-sky-50 p-6 rounded-lg shadow-inner">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-700 mb-2">1. Axial Skeleton (80 bones)</h4>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-slate-600">
                                <li>Forms the central axis of the body.</li>
                                <li>Includes: Skull (22 bones), Vertebral Column (26 bones), Rib Cage (24 ribs + sternum).</li>
                                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Protects the brain, spinal cord, heart, and lungs.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-sky-50 p-6 rounded-lg shadow-inner">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-700 mb-2">2. Appendicular Skeleton (126 bones)</h4>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-slate-600">
                                <li>Forms the limbs and girdles.</li>
                                <li>Includes: Pectoral and Pelvic Girdles, Upper and Lower Limbs.</li>
                                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Enables movement and locomotion.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Types of Bones Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Types of Bones</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 mb-4">
                        Bones are classified by shape and structure:
                    </p>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 text-slate-600">
                        <p><strong>Long Bones:</strong> Support weight and enable movement (e.g., femur, humerus).</p>
                        <p><strong>Short Bones:</strong> Provide stability with limited movement (e.g., carpals, tarsals).</p>
                        <p><strong>Flat Bones:</strong> Protect organs and provide surfaces for muscle attachment (e.g., skull, sternum).</p>
                        <p><strong>Irregular Bones:</strong> Complex shapes with specialized functions (e.g., vertebrae, mandible).</p>
                        <p><strong>Sesamoid Bones:</strong> Small, round bones embedded in tendons (e.g., patella).</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Joints Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Joints of the Skeletal System</h3>
                    <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 mb-4">
                        Joints (articulations) are where two or more bones meet. They allow different types of movement:
                    </p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                        <li><strong>Fibrous Joints:</strong> Immovable (e.g., skull sutures).</li>
                        <li><strong>Cartilaginous Joints:</strong> Slightly movable (e.g., intervertebral discs).</li>
                        <li><strong>Synovial Joints:</strong> Freely movable and most common (e.g., knee, shoulder, hip).</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <!-- Bone Composition & Health Section -->
                <div class="mb-8">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-sky-600 mb-4">Bone Composition & Health</h3>
                    <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6">
                        <div class="flex-1">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-700 mb-2">Bone Composition</h4>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-slate-600">
                                <li><strong>Compact Bone:</strong> Dense outer layer providing strength.</li>
                                <li><strong>Spongy Bone:</strong> Lightweight inner structure containing red marrow.</li>
                                <li><strong>Bone Marrow:</strong> Red marrow produces blood cells; yellow marrow stores fat.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div class="flex-1">
                            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-sky-700 mb-2">Tips for Healthy Bones</h4>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-slate-600">
                                <li>Eat a balanced diet rich in calcium and vitamin D.</li>
                                <li>Engage in weight-bearing exercise like walking or running.</li>
                                <li>Avoid smoking and excessive alcohol.</li>
                                <li>Maintain proper posture and body weight.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>


